You can use [generics](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/programming-guide/generics/generic-methods) to create a `ReceiveSet` which doesn&#39;t expect a `Func&lt;object, object&gt;` object, but instead a `Func&lt;T, U&gt;` object, where `T` and `U` can be specified via generic parameters. Then the argument you try to use will fit:

    public void ReceiveSet&lt;T,U&gt;(Func&lt;T, U&gt; func) {
    }

You can use this method as follow:

    ReceiveSet&lt;B, A&gt;(SetA);
    ReceiveSet&lt;D, C&gt;(SetC);

*(adjust for static/non-static use of course)*

In the first call it expect a `Func&lt;B,A&gt;` object/reference, which your `SetA` method is. In the second call it expect now a `Func&lt;D,C&gt;` object/reference, which your `SetC` method is.

